[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626808&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626808&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

CNAMEs establish one name as an alias for another.  CNAMEs work for one
name, they don't alias whole subtrees.

The reasons it was defined this way include:

*	it seemed that "whole tree" aliasing would add complexity
	to the search and servers.

*	it wasn't clear how one could use CNAMEs in a cache.  Part of
	the problem is that we have a general principle that a parent
	can't force inherited characteristics on children.  Another is
	deciding on which names exist/don't exist.

*	it would be easy enough to generate the CNAMEs if you really
	wanted to do equivalence whole domains, while it would be
	relatively harder to provide for exceptions.

Regardless of whether this is the right or wrong idea, that's the way
that the software is supposed to work, and I believe the way that
its implemented in general.  It could have gone the other way.  See
X.500 for an example.

paul

